column168: THERE WERE TWO DRUMS SHRINKWRAPPED ONTO A SKID. THIS SKID WAS LOADED ABOUT EIGHT FEET FROM THE REAR OF THE TRAILER. WHEN THE FORK DRIVER ENTERED THE TRAILER, THE FORK BLADES WERE VERY LOW. HOWEVER, WHEN THE REAR OF THE FORK ENTERED THE TRAILER, THIS LOWERED THE REAR OF THE FORKLIFT AND THEREFORE RAISED THE BLADES IN THE FRONT. THE INEXPERIENCED FORK DRIVER WAS NOT READY FOR THIS AND HIS BLADES ACCIDENTLY STRUCK THE DRUM INSTEAD OF GOING INTO THE PALLET. THE RESULT IS A FORK PUNCTURE NEAR THE BASE OF THE DRUM. THE WRAP WAS REMOVED AND THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS LAID ON IT’S SIDE WITH THE HOLE FACING UP TO PREVENT ADDITIONAL SPILLAGE.
column169: INEXPERIENCED FORK DRIVERS MUST BE VERY CLOSELY SUPERVISED AND TRAINED. THE WORD HAS TO BE UNDERSTOOD THAT WHEN THE LEVEL OF THE ATTITUDE FORK CHANGES, THEN THIS WILL AUTOMATICALLY CHANGE THE HEIGHT OF THE FORK BLADES. EXTRA CAUTION MUST TAKE PLACE WHEN HANDLING DRUMS.

column168: On 9/8/06, a Veolia driver was delivering a loaded trailer to the Veolia TSD located in Phoenix, AZ.  Prior to arrival at the facility, the driver stopped on Jefferson Street immediately to the west of the facility in order to obtain parking/unloading instructions.  Upon return to the vehicle, the driver noticed a small leak from the trailer.  After further investigation, Veolia facility personnel determined a pole mount transformer being transported had tipped over inside the trailer.  At this time Veolia site personnel immediately began to contain the spill and stop the leak.      Upon entering the trailer it was confirmed that one pole mount transformer with a capacity of 15 gallons and a PCB concentration of 240 ppm PCB oil had tipped over in the trailer.  The transformer was placed in an upright position and the spill was contained.  Oil that had dripped out of the trailer as well as any areas on the ground where the oil had leaked were cleaned up by double washing/rinsing with kerosene/diesel/soap and water.      After the spill was contained, the trailer was parked at the loading dock and the material was removed from the trailer.  The trailer floor was then decontaminated using the same procedure of double wash/double rinse of the affected area.  The spill event lasted approximately 15 minutes and was cleaned up done immediately.    Veolia estimates that no more than 10 gallons of oil were spilled but the generator states maximum oil in unit to be 15 gallons of oil.  The driver was disciplined for failure to properly secure the shipment.
column169: Ensure that any container being transported is suitable for highway transportation.  Lids must be secure, the material must be secured to pallet and load locks, straps or braces must be used inside the trailer to prevent the material from shifting or tipping over.  Transformers are top heavy and must be secured to prevent this event from happening.  Veolia trains drivers in the safe transportation of hazardous materials and reviews every incident and shares the investigation results with the drivers.  A special bulletin will be provided to the drivers reminding them of proper cargo securement responsibilities and procedures.

column168: According to the information obtained the following is known.  While unloading six cylinders from a trailer using a forklift one cylinder was damaged.  Approximately 30 gallons of product was released into the air.  BAX Global, Inc. personnel contained the spill and removed the damaged cylinder and remaining shipment from the trailer using special gloves, mask and protective shield.  No actual cleanup was necessary due to the release evaporating.  The undamaged goods will be forwarded to the consignee.  The damaged container will be stored in the DG area until further notification.
column169: BAX Global, Inc. implements safety procedures daily but since the release was accidental, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence

column168: A telephone report was received notifying the receiver that material that "smelled like nail polish remover" had leaked from a cargo tank onto their vehicle on west bound I 70 outside of Indianapolis.  Upon receipt of the notice, the cargo tank had arrived at the destination.  Upon investigation, it was determined that the gasket on the man hole cover had been crimped.  The gasket was folded over, and did not completely seal.  It is surmised that a minimal amount of lacquer thinner leaked past the seal and blew from the top of the cargo tank.  No damage was reported.  The cargo tank was taken out of service for repair and inspection.
column169: Notified shipper and driver of seal failure.  Procedures implemented to inspect gaskets prior to securement of manhole cover.

column168: At approximately 2:30pm on September, 13 2006 a tanker trailer operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc (CHES) experienced a minor release of hazardous material (specification used fuel oil) from a bulk package.  At the time of the release the vehicle was entering the off-loading pad at the storage area of Pike Industries in South Portland, ME.  While driving up an incline to the off-loading area, the driver noticed oil coming out the drain tubes in the back of the trailer.  He immediately stopped the vehicle, and proceeded to the back of the trailer.  Upon arriving at the back of the trailer he noticed oil seeping out of the middle dome cover.  The driver decided to move the trailer to a level ground to prevent any additional material leaking out.      The driver then notified his dispatch of the incident, applied available spill control material to the spill and awaited the arrival of the clean up crew.   Concurrently, the supervisor notified Maine Department of Environmental Protection via phone of the incident and a representative arrive on the scene around 3:30pm.    We estimate that approximately 30 gallons of fuel oil leaked out onto the secondary containment.  An in-house response crew conducted a thorough spill clean up operation, placed all contaminated materials into appropriate containers for disposal at a fully permitted waste management facility.  The remainder of the material was offloaded from the tanker into a storage tank and the tanker truck was placed out of service until the cause of the leak could be determined and repaired.      Our initial investigation found that one of the dome cover vents was out of adjustments and had failed to perform as designed.
column169: In response to this event, the vehicle in question was placed out of service and taken to a repair shop for maintenance.  The man-ways will be checked for tolerances and all necessary adjustments will be made.      Additionally, the tanker will not be loaded with greater than 8,000 gallons of material and at temperature not greater than 140 degrees Fahrenheit.

column168: Transport was traveling on a muddy private crude oil lease road when driver lost traction and slid into drainage ditch.  The load then shifted and caused the tractor trailer to overturn.  No product was lost.  There were no injuries sustained by the driver. The driver promptly reported event and company responded with recovery services.  The load of crude oil was transferred to another transport. Wrecker services uprighted the transport and towed it away from scene. No other cleanup was required. Damages to the cargo tank included minor shallow dents, and damaged appurtenances.
column169: Reinforce to company drivers the inherent risks of driving on non-improved roadways during inclement weather conditions; Use good judgement and be more conservative when assessing off road conditions; Do not commit to questionably safe roads where turn arounds are not available.

column168: This shipment was being audited by "TAG" (The Adherence Group) who is contracted to inspect shipments to ensure that what is being declared on the bill of labing is what is actually being shipped.  Tag found the fire extinguishers in the shipment but no corresponding hazardous materials documentation.  The shipment was placed on hold until the shipper could provide updated compliant documentation.  No placards were required since the shipment was moving in "Limited Quantities".
column169: It seems that the random checks by both the US Coast Guard as well as agencies such as "TAG" serve as a deterrant to shippers who provide incomplete documentation resulting in undeclared hazardous materials shipments.  Perhaps, the periodic random auditing of containerized cargo by carriers, the US Coast Guard and independent agencies such as "TAG" will aid shippers in meeting the regulatory compliance requirements.

column168: The shipper tendered the shipment to the carrier but did not book nor declare the shipment as hazardous.  An associate of the carrier questioned the documentation for the shipment and asked the customer specifically if the cargo was hazardous.  The customer indicated that it was hazardous but is no longer hazardous once unloaded from the original container.  The associate copied me in on the e-mail inquiry of the customer.  I asked the customer to provide the regulatory reference showing that the shipment is non hazardous.  He did not immediately answer so I phoned the customer to discuss the issue with him.  He still indicated that the shipment was non hazardous.  I, knowing differently, asked his to chat with the hazmat help desk with the DOT.  The help desk associate confirmed our understanding of the shipment of two containers.  The customer then provided all of the required hazardous materials documentation for the shipment which was already in transit via rail to the ocean terminal for loading aboard our cargo vessel.  Instructions were given to hold the shipments to to apply the class 9 marking with the UN number.
column169: This problem was caught by one of our trained hazmat associates at the marine terminal.  Trained associates combined with random inspections are the elements required to provide a good safety net in promoting hazmat safety.

column168: Based on information from the West Virginia State Police, our unit had been traveling south on WV Route 18, transporting gasoline and diesel fuel to a local gas station.  Upon passing the Chevron fuel station, located along the west roadway edge of WV Rt. 18, and entering a left hand turn, our vehicle traveled off the west roadway edge, striking the guardrail.  Subsequently, our unit turned over in the roadway coming to rest on its passenger side.  According to witness statements, our unit immediately burst into flames, starting at the rear resulting in multiple explosions.  Due to our unit sustaining extensive damage due to the fire it would be immpossible to conclude if the accident was caused by mechanical failure.  Also, of the witnesses interviewed none could provide information indicative to our unit showing signs of mechanical failure; ie, tire smoke, erratic weaving, heavy braking, etc.
column169: Upon receiving all information from the authorities, this will be used as a teaching tool.

column168: Driver had completed transferring product from cargo tank to customer storage tank using a pump.  Because of the distance and elevation that the product had to travel, driver couldn't clear the lines so he used some air pressure.  He stated he relieved the pressure before disconnecting the hose from the trailer but it appears that there was probably still a little pressure in the line that caused some product to be squirted on his clothes when he disconnected.  He didn't notice it because his clothes were wet from perspiration.  When driver departed from the facility, he rolled up his shirt sleeves and noticed a burning sensation on the inside joint of his arm. He showered when he got back to our facility and then again when he got home. He treated the irritation with ointment for 3 days before reporting the incident to us.  We sent him to the clinic to be checked out.  An ointment was prescribed and driver was released to full duty with no lost time.
column169: The prescribed PPE for corrosive products includes chemical suit, face shield, goggles, gloves, etc.  The driver was not wearing the correct PPE.  He was wearing hard hat, safety glasses and gloves.  Had he been wearing the correct PPE, the injury would not have happened.  We are constantly stressing to drivers the importance of wearing the correct PPE via newsletters, fleet messages, safety training, etc.

column168: According to the information obtained the following occurred. While stationary at Slay Transportation Co., Inc. facility, a leak occurred in the rear end offloading valve causing approximately 0.5 quarts of product release. Apparently, the release was caused by freezing in the offloading valve. When the release was discovered a bucket was placed under the valve to prevent further leakage. Slay Transportation Co., Inc. performed cleanup of the free product. The waste generated as a result of this incident was placed into a plastic bag pending disposal. Slay Transportation Co., Inc. will handle disposal of the waste generated. There were no injuries or exposures reported. The MSDS was requested and received.
column169: Since the release was accidental, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence. However, Slay Transportation Co., Inc. will continue to reinforce safety guidelines and handling procedures.

column168: The Gas Company, LLC (TGC)employee was driving a tractor trailer transporting liquefied petroleum gas (LPG) heading West on Highway 19 approaching the intersection of Hwy 19 and Plumeria Street.  A Ford Ranger was traveling along Plumeria Street heading South towards the T-intersection with Highway 19.  According to the Police Report, the Ford Ranger disregarded the stop line on Plumeria Street and entered Highway 19 and Plumeria Street intersection.  The TGC driver applied the tractor brakes but could not stop in time and collided with the Ford Ranger.  The Ford Ranger then struck the sedan behind it, which was stopped at the intersection of Plumeria Street and Highway 19.  The driver of the Ford Ranger was unresponsive, therefore, 911 was called and the driver was taken to the hospital.    Damage to the TGC tractor trailer was limited to the front section of the tractor and did not result in any product release.
column169: TGC's initial investigation did not come up with any significant changes to prevent recurrences.  TGC will continue to evaluate reasonable recommendations for improvements.

column168: Motor carrier (cargo tank motor vehicle) traveling north bound, rear-ended an automobile which was stopped in the roadway; both automobile and tractor were consumed by fire; automobile driver, a 77 year old male, was killed; truck driver was not injured. Truck driver did not see automobile in time to avoid collision. [Accident occurred at 23:15 hours]    Fire Departments from Saraland and Mobile, AL responded preventing the fire from seriously damaging the cargo tank trailer.     Saraland Police Department reports that the automobile driver may have had a tire problem and was stopped in the roadway with its lights off. Witnesses state that the automobile did not have its light on at the time of the collision.     After minor repairs to the cargo tank trailer at the accident site, the cargo tank trailer was transported to another motor carrier’s property and the shipment of acrylic acid was transferred to another cargo tank motor vehicle. Temperature of the acrylic acid after transfer was 77 degrees.  Shipment was returned to shipper.     Motor carrier believes that the DOT 407 construction and fire departments actions prevented the acrylic acid from undergoing violent polymerization.
column169: Motor carrier has no recomendations at this time.

column168: On 9/22/06, at 08:00 am, a trailer of drums arrived at the Veolia, Sauget IL facility for unloading.  Upon opening the trailer doors it was found that one fiber drum had fallen over due to improper bracing.  The lid was off and 10 gallons of material spilled in the trailer and in the concrete secondary containment area.  The material was solid efferdent tablets so the material was swept, placed back in the fiber drum, and the lid secured.  There was no release to the environment and the material will be incinerated.
column169: The offeror and/or transporter need to place the bracing immediately next to the drums and not leave a gap between the drum and the support beam, which in this case caused the drum to tip over.

When unloading freight from trailer forklift operator went to go and remove a pallet of plastic jerricans with the forklift that he was operating. When he placed the forkblades through the proper opening in the pallet he went about halfwalf into the pallet when he observed liquid coming from that area. He immediately stopped and looked to investigate the cause. Here the pallet that was used by the shipper to stage the jerricans on was a poor grade pallet and just could not support the weight of them. As a result the center slats of the pallet caused the pallet to collapse in the middle causing the jerricans to sink downward into the path of the oncoming forkblades. The spilled material was cleaned with sorbent material and placed into a recovery container along with the damaged jerricans. The remaining jerricans where re-staged on a better quality pallet and shipped to ultimate consignee without further incident.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While unloading at the BAX Global facility, a leak was discovered.  Upon inspection, it appeared that two fiberboard cartons had been crushed in transit.  Each carton contained two (1) one-liter plastic bottles.  Three (3) one-liter plastic bottles were damaged.  The free product released inside the trailer and onto the asphalt surface beneath the trailer.  BAX Global Inc. personnel performed the cleanup with the application of absorbent material to the free product.  The spent material was containerized into a recovery drum, along with the damaged containers, pending disposal per local, state, and federal regulations.  There were no injuries or exposures reported.
column169: Since the release as accidental, and appears to be related to the freight shifting in transit, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.  BAX Global Inc. will continue to reinforce safety guidelines and safe handling procedures to all personnel, and enforce strict carrier regulations to all transport carriers.

column168: The incident mentioned in this report occurred on private property owned by the motor carrier located at 2403 7th Avenue, Camanche, Iowa.  The trailer was loaded in West Burlington, Iowa and brought to Camanche, IA for later movement to Arlington, Heights, IL.  The power unit was unhooked from the trailer.  The trailer was dollied down onto a concrete dolly pad.  The dolly pad was approximately 160 feet long, 4 feet wide, 10 inches thick and in 8 foot sections.  Approximately one hour after the trailer had been unhooked/parked, the President of the Company was in the equipment yard and noticed that the trailer had started a slow roll to the trailer's left side.  The trailer rolled approximately 270 degrees clockwise (looking at the front of the trailer)and settled back to approximately 220 degrees from being up right.  The leak from the cargo tank started from around the Dome Cover.  No other leaks.  The leak of Ethanol lasted approximately 2 hours.  The Camanche, Iowa Fore Department and Police Department were notified and were on the scene in a matter of minutes of being notified.  The Fire Department installed a clamp on the Dome cover of the trailer

The drum was placed in an approved recovery receptical and forwarded back to E I Dupont on Pro# 027-1290792 per the original shippers request. The release was contained and managed in approx. 30 minutes. The released material was absorbed in to the floor and the residue was cleaned up with a heavy fluids mat approved for flammable liquids and placed in a small metal pail to be disposed of according to regulations.
column169: The company training designates drums be moved is a specific manner, the procedure does not allow single drums to be moved by forklift. column168: According to the information obtain the following occurred. While unloading a leak was discover in one(1) fifty-five gallon drum in the shipment. Approximately, 10 gallons of free product was released. La Porte Police and La Porte Fire Department responded to assess the site. The La Porte Fire Department used absorbents to contain the free product. Garner Environmental Services of Deer Park, TX were contacted to assist with cleanup. Garner Environmental Services placed additional absorbent clay and absorbent pads to complete containment. Garner Environmental offloaded the affected trailer. 10 pallets were discovered to be affected from this incident. The affected drum was transported back to Dow Chemical in Houston, TX. Garner Environmental placed the spent material and affected pallets onto a roll-off. Garner Environmental Services will coordinate disposal of the waste generated.

column168: LATE PM ON 9/1/06 AND EARLY AM ON 9/2/06, THERE WAS SEVERE RAIN IN JUNEAU AK.  OUR VEHICLE WAS PARKED IN AN AREA ABOVE LEMON CREEK.  BECAUSE OF HEAVY RAIN, LEMON CREEK ERODED EMBANKMENT.  EMBANKMENT WAS ERODED CAUSING OUR VEHICLE, CONTAINING APPROX. 76 GALLONS OF ACETIC ACID SOLUTION, TO FALL INTO THE SWOLLEN CREEK.  THE TRUCK BODY WAS DAMAGED CAUSING THE DRUMS TO ACCESS THE CREEK.  THE RAPIDS IN THE CREEK CAUSED THE DRUMS TO BE PUNCTURED RELEASING THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL INTO THE CREEK.  US COAST GUARD NOTIFIED AUSTIN POWDER COMPANY OF INCIDENT.  STATE OF AK, DEPT. column168: On September 9, 2006, at approximately 1141 hours, a railway tankcar NATX 73906, loaded with Corrosive Liquids, N.O.S., corrosive, UN1267 PG Il, was reported leaking at the Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) Alexandria Louisiana yard. The tank car was discovered leaking from the manway cover, the gasket was not tool tight and also needed to be replaced. The shipper representative responded to the site, replaced the gasket and tool tightened the manway. There were no injuries, no damage to the environment.  CODE: 212  NARRI: 5(5÷5+0)x(2+0)=100
column169: On The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR), shippers are immediately notified of all HAZMAT releases. For non-accident releases (a.k.a. package or closure defects), where possible, shippers (responsible party) are requested to respond, repair and remediate. By immediately involving the shipper, in-depth knowledge of the release cause is gained by the same organization that can implement process changes to prevent recurrence. After each NAR incident, KCSR provides outreach to the shipper to help investigate root-cause factors for correction. For non-accident related releases, the shipper should be contacted directly for details associated with actions taken to prevent recurrence.

column168: An import container of 13 SS drums of SC Concentrate (part 843201)was being returned to FUJIFILM US from FUJIFILM Taiwan. The container had blocking & bracing but our broker advised that it was rejected by BNSF in CA because they determined the loading did not meet standards for intermodal rail transit. The drayage company, CALKO Transport performed the services to inspect,block & brace, and reseal for transit.     When it arrived at Intransit's rail ramp /yard, in Worcester, MA, it was removed from rail & transfered to a chassis, a leak was noticed from the container. The spill is resin based so the solvent based resin dried on the floor with the solvents quickly evaporating.     Intransit placed calls to our company & notified CHEMTREC. The MA DEP & Worcester Fire Department were called to the Intransit's site. We authorized our emergency repsonse contractor, Clean Harbors to respond, clean-up the spill, and handle resulting disposal.      It was dtermined that the spill was caused by a puncture to one drum from a protruding nail from adjacent wood bracing at the front nose of the container. It was evident that the nail rubbed /vibrated around the side of the drum before it became a punctured. We are addressing this issue with CALKO TRANSPORT in Compton CA.
column169: We have requested CALKO investigate their blocking & bracing procedures and areas identify areas for improvement.       We have notified our office in Taiwan on the the intermodal rail standards

column168: This cargo tank is a specialty trailer in which the internal valve, external valve, and unloading pump are located inside of a box on the trailer.  After loading, the box is sealed. The external was left open and capped off.  When driver picked up the trailer, he couldn't pretrip that part of it.  When he got to the consignee, the unloader broke the seal and removed the unloading cap and 1/2 gallon splashed out onto the unloaders boot and ground. Evidently some product had gotten into the discharge line from loading or the internal was not completely sealed. Absorbant pads were used for cleanup.
column169: Whoever loaded the trailer did not follow procedure by making sure all the valves were properly closed and secured.

column168: Trailer was dropped in the North Charleston yard to be delivered next day.  Local Driver noticed Trailer was slightly dripping under the center of the trailer.  Shippers bill of lading stated product loaded was 6707 gallons.  The only trailer available was a 6700 gallon tanker. In process of transferring the product, driver was watching levels at different intervels of the transloading process.  While in process of climbing the ladder of the tanker, product reached the dome and spilled onto the ground.  Driver shut pump off and clean up was preformed. Local Fire Dept, DHEC and Moran Enviromental Recovery were on site.  Gravel and dirt were collected into a rolloff and disposed by Moran Enviromental.
column169: Strick company polices are in place for drivers to ensure all trailer transloading procedures are enfored. Driver will be retrained on procedure for transloading product and in addition on spill prevention at the companies training and developing center in Kingsport TN.  Remedial spill prevention training is also administered to Drivers who are identifed as having problems.  Spill prevention training is also given to drivers at least annually at their respective terminal.

column168: VEHICLE TURNED OVER WHEN MAKING A SHARP LEFT TURN FROM HOLT ROAD ONTO RAMP TO EASTBOUND I-70. A FIRST RESPONDER WAS PROMPTLY CALLED TO CLEAN UP THE AREA AFFECTED AND EXCAVATED APPROXIMATELY 800 TONS OF EARTH.
column169: PRESIDENT OF SWITZER TANK LINES INC, HAS SPOKEN TO DRIVER REGARDING THE CIRCUMSTANCES AND DETAILS OF THE ACCIDENT, AND IT’S IMPACT ON SWITZER TANK LINES AND THE ENVIRONMENT.  DRIVER DRUG TEST WAS NEGATIVE.  DRIVERS STATUS WAS CHANGE TO PROBATIONARY RATHER THAN TERMINATED DUE TO ALMOST DRIVING AND WORK RECORD.  PRESIDENT OF SWITZER TANK LINES ALSO MET WITH EACH SWITZER DRIVER INDIVIDUALLY REGARDING THE CIRCUMSTANCES AND DETAILS OF THE ACCIDENT.  DRIVERS WERE ADVISED THAT ALL SPEED REDUCTIONS MUST BE COMPLETE PRIOR TO TURNING.  THIS MESSAGE WILL BE REPEATED AND REINFORCED AT THE NEXT SCHEDULED SAFETY MEETING.  SEE ATTACHED LETTER DATED 09-26-2006.

column168: Maleic Anhydride, Molten was being transferred from a disabled cargo tank to another cargo tank. The operator stopped the transfer to change fittings. Operator openned hose connection without verifying that product had been flushed from hose, causing a release of < 5 gallons of product which aerosoled and solidified causing eye irritation to the 2 employees doing the transfer. Emergency response by company and EMS arrived within 5 minutes. The two employees were decontaminated by EMS personnel. They were taken to Macneal hospital where they were treated and released. Three EMS employees who did the transport were also treated for exposure to acidic fumes and released. Company initiated cleanup of powdered product that was released and completed cleanup within 45 minutes of the release. All product residue recovered from spill scene, no residue remained.
column169: Operator debriefed at scene and admitted not following proper procedure before disconnecting hose. He will receive remedial training and observed closely for proper safety procedures.

column168: Trailer was dropped on the yard in Sherman, TX on 9/23/06 with no apparent leakage at that time. On the morning of 9/25/06 at approximately 0730 the trailer was found with substance leaking out of the back door and onto the gravel yard. Upon bringing the trailer to the dock the shipment was found to be leaking and on further examination a small crack was approximately an inch long was found on one of the bottom corners of the plastic portion of the tote about 9"-12" from the bottom. It is unknown how long the tote leaked over the weekend since we don’t know when it started however, approximately 70 gallons of the material was released before it was contained. Due to the size of the incident, TAS Environmental out of Ft. Worth, TX was brought in to contain and clean up the released material.
column169: It appears that this was a packaging failure on the shippers part. This material was shipped in a 330 gallon plastic tote with a metal cage construction around it. There is no evidence that the metal portion of the package was damaged in any way yet the plastic portion of the tote has a hairline seam on one corner.

Driver was using a pump to transfer product from cargo tank to customer storage tank.  Product is thick.  About 15 minutes into the unload, the rubber part of the hose, that was attached to the pump outlet, separated from it's end fitting.  About 5 gallons spilled out and customer cleaned up with oil dry.  Driver replaced that section of hose and started to unload again when he determined the product was not moving and the pump was getting hot.  He shut down.  It was finally determined that the customer storage tank was brand new and the check valve had been installed backwards.  Product could not move through it, building up pressure in the hose, causing it to fail.
column169: Valve on customer storage tank was installed backwards. Human error.

column168: Shipment was received at unloading facility with one 5 gallon pail damaged.  Pail was overturned and crushed by other freight in trailer due to improper bracing and lack of dunnage.  Approximately 2 gallons of contents released.  Spill was contained on inbound trailer and cleaned up using absorbent compound.  Remainder of shipment that was undamaged was recouped an sent to destination.  Damaged pail and spent absorbent compound held in haz mat bay of unloading facility for disposal via environmental contractor.

At approximately 7:00 AM on 09/18/06, a UN lAl closed head steel 55 gallon drum containing a liquid mixture of methacrylate monomer material experienced a reaction within the container causing the drum to over pressurize and rupture. The force of the pressure release resulted in the top portion of the drum being torn of and partial forced ejection of the drum’s contents. Please note that at the time of the incident the container was located in a fully contained section of a concrete floor warehouse at Clean Harbors in-transit storage facility located at 2858 Route 322, Bridgeport, NJ. A facility employee was working in the warehouse at that time and upon hearing the noise associated with the rupture of the container, immediately evacuated the area and contacted the facility’s Emergency Response Coordinator (ERC).  The surrounding area was secured with caution tape and orange cones pending the arrival of appropriate emergency response personnel. An in-house emergency response crew arrived to the warehouse within minutes to assess the situation. Utili:ing appropriate personal protection equipment, and company health and safety procedures, the emergency response personnol entered the warehouse in order to identify the material involved. Upon reviewing the material markings and labels, it was determine I that the material involved was a shipment of hazardous Waste flammable liquid, n.o.s. (methyl methacrylate, ethyl methacrylate 3, UN 1993, PGII picked up from Keystone Industries on 09/13/06 on EPA hazardous waste manifest 000686252FLE. It was also determined that out of 14 drums shipped only one had undergone rupture and release. The liquid methacrylate monomer had polymeriz d causing the drum to over pressurize and rupture. The resulting release scattered the reacted material throughout a large section of the warehouse. Some of the material hit the ceiling of the warehouse knocking down insulation and lodging in the ceiling 1-beams. All of the released material was contained within the warehouse and the threat of release to the environment was not present. The ERC retrieved the appropriate shipping papers and notified the shipper of the incident and asked for guidance. No immediate clean up action was taken due to concern for the remaining 13 drums undergoing a similar reaction.  See additional sheet for continuation.
column169: Immediately following this incident, the approval to ship the waste stream involved in this incident was suspended pending an investigation conducted by the shipper of the material.    In order to prevent a recurrence of such incident, the shipper of this material has been asked to review their internal operating procedures to ensure the safety and stability of this waste stream. Further shipments of this material may resume, pending the outcome of Keystone Industry’s internal investigation and findings.

Driver was transferring product from cargo tank to customer's storage tank.  It was a 4000 gallon storage tank with 1600 in it according to the reading on the sight gauge.  Driver was using pump to transfer the 2000 gallons of product from cargo tank to the storage tank.  Storage tank overflowed from a vent on the very top of tank when only 1000 gallons had been transferred.  After the overflow, the sight gauge was reading only 3300 gallons.  Spilled product went into a steel containment area around the tank.
column169: Customer is aware that accuracy of sight gauge needs to be checked.

column168: The drum was sent from the shipper on a skid which was noticed to be leaking upon arrival to the origin terminal. The skid had a nail protruding which caused a small mark in the bottom of the drum, causing a small release from the bottom of the drum. The drum was placed in a neutral postion and placed in a recovery drum. The product was returned to Dupont. The release was managed in 30 minutes with minimal exposeure.

GATX TANK CAR WAS OBSERVED BY BELT RAILWAY CARMAN ON AN OUTBOUND TRAIN WITH A SMALL LEAK COMING FROM BOTTOM OUTLET.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE BOTTOM VALVE WAS NOT COMPLETELY CLOSED.  THE BOTTOM OUTLET WAS GIVEN 1/2 TURN AND THE LEAK STOPPED.  THE TANK CAR WAS CHECKED BY CARMAN AND EVERYTHING WAS SECURE. MINOR LEAK OF ALCOHOL.  TANK CAR WAS RELEASED FOR TRANSPORT N.O.S.
column169: IT APPEARS THE TANK CAR VALVE WAS NOT SECURED DURING TRANSPORT.  THE BELT RAILWAY CHECKS ALL CARS ENTERING AND EXITING THE YARD.  DURING THE CHECK THE LEAK WAS SPOTTED AND SECURED.  BECAUSE OF PROPER TRAINING OF BELT EMPLOYEES THE LEAK WAS SECURED.

At approximately 11:10 the railcar loader checked railcar UTLX 12726 which he was back loading with spent acid.  The railcar had 12” to 18” to go before the level reached the loading marker.  The loader needed to use the restroom and left the loading rack.  He went to the Morgan building which is situated on the East side of the rack and removed his goggles, respirator, and protective jacket.  The loader then used the “Porta-Potty” which is located across the street from the loading rack.  Upon exiting the restroom at 11:16 he noticed the railcar was running over.  He then ran to the Morgan building and put his respirator, goggles, and protective jacket back on.  He quickly shut down the loading pump and blocked in the spent acid loading valve.

column168: On 9/26/2006 at approximately 4:30 AM, a KC Industries Trucking Driver was at the TECO Polk Power Station facility on State Road 37, loading sulfuric acid.   The Driver had completed the load and had left the fill station when he remembered that he failed to secure the dome lid on the tanker.  The Driver stopped his vehicle and got out to shut the dome lid.  At this point, the Driver realized that acid had leaked out and spilled on the asphalt as he was leaving the fill station.  He returned to the containment area to report the incident to the Operator.   The Operator contacted the Environmental Coordinator.   The Driver reported the incident to KC Industries Trucking Terminal Manager and Safety Director.    KC Industries Trucking contacted American Compliance Technologies; Inc. (ACT) to clean up the spill - 40 to 50 gallons.
column169: Corrective Actions:  1. Communicated accident to all drivers, reinforcing the importance of sealing the dome lids.   2. Re-Trained Drivers on shutting and sealing dome lids.  4. Non-conformance warning issued to Driver and loss of Safety Quarterly Bonus.

column168: Delivery driver mistakenly delivered fuel oil into the kerosene UST resulting in an overflow from that tank.  The overflow was further aggravated by a short cycle high warning alarm and a 2-inch plug that had been removed from the top of the kerosene tank.  Penn Tank Lines called National response and PA One-call number to report the incident.  PA-DEP, local fire departments, Penn Tank Lines’ Spill Responder, and Penn Tank Lines personnel responded to the scene.
column169: Suburban Energy responsibilities should include:   Clean all inlet valves so colors are readably identifiable.  Label or tag with product description all inlet valves.  Change overfill alarm monitor to sound longer than the short 10-second alarm currently used.  Move alarm from side of terminal building to loading rack area (it is currently not visible when tank truck is delivering).  To minimize overflow from area around tank man ways make sure all plugs are properly placed.     Instruct terminal personnel as to Federal & State reporting requirements for spill response.    Penn Tank responsibilities should include:  Current site reports to all drivers for S. E. locations.  Require drivers making deliveries to verify by tracing loading lines from valve inlet to tank to insure that they are delivering into the correct tank.  Instruct drivers on their responsibility as to cross drop and spill reporting to Penn Tank along with the instruction that they are not to leave the terminal area where the cross drop or spill occurred until released by Penn Tank management.

column169: The customer did not declare their hazardous cargo to us (a carrier) at time of loading the hazardous cargo on the vessel from the US port.   The customer also did not apply the placards on the exterior of the container at time of delivering to the port.  In this case, the US DOT should give a penalty fine for Undeclared hazardous cargo to this customer.  It is normally, when the customer is involving a penalty with the authority, they really take seriously and do something about to avoid doing again.

column168: During the loading process from railroad tank to highway cargo tank, operator left bleed valve on loading line in the open position.  Material leaked onto ground before it was discovered by operator.  Operator shutdown loading process, closed valve, and notified his supervisor.  Company notified local fire department and environmental response contractor.  Fire department assessed hazards and environmental response contractor neutralized spilled material and recovered it in three 55-gallon open top drums.  Material transported off-site for disposal.
column169: Standard operating procedures were modified to require the use of removalable caps on the bleed valve opening before transferring material through the loading line.

column168: During sulfuric acid (93%) unloading operations at the Unit 5 Acid Tank, the recieving tank overflowed into a diked area beneath the tank.  Upon observing the overflow, the truck driver / unloading operator immediately secured the transfer evolution.  The acid overflowed for approximately 30 seconds.  Prior to unloading the plant operator verified that there was adaquate room for the load of acid.  The recieving tank is approximately 6000 gallons. The initial tank volume was 2368 gallons before initiating the unloading evolution.  The tank overflowed with the guage reading 4924 gallons.  The tank level/volume instrumentation appears to be out of calibration and reading incorrectly.  About 60 gallons was spilled into the containment areas beneath the tank.  The spilled acid was neutralized and flushed with fresh water to the plant's waste system for treatment by plant personnel.  No offsite release occurred and no personnel were injured.
column169: The Unit 5 acid tank level/volume instrumentation will be evaluated.  The instrument will be repaired or replaced, calibrated, and verified to operate correctly.  Meanwhile, instructions were made for plant operators to order acid at an indicated tank level of 2000 gallons verses 3000 gallons so that adaquate tank freeboard will be available.  The practice of ordering acid is normally done at 2000 gallons indicated tank level.  This practice was altered during hurricane season to order acid at 3000 gallons based upon lessons learned during Hurricane Katrina.

Once the tank car is cleaned, it will be released for movement onto the local consignee.

column14: BNSF MP 249.6 MAIN TRACK, FT W
column168: A BNSF train derailed 24 railcars on single main track, including 7 tank cars ladened with hazardous material. The cause of this derailment was a stiff truck bolster which contributed to improper swiveling on the first railcar derailing. One of the derailed tank cars, DOWX 40077, on its side released product. The A-end tank head of DOWX 40077 sustained a head puncture approximately sized at 6 inches by 12 inches at the 7 o’clock position, caused by contact with other derailing rail equipment, most likely a coupler head. This puncture hole was facing towards the ground over a cement culvert for a drainage ditch which ran perpendicular to the main track. Escaping product flowed into this ditch and the responding local F.D. dammed the ditch, limiting the flow impact of the escaping product. Contract responders vacuumed all free standing product in the ditch. Hydrochloric acid was applied to the impacted soil in the ditch to neutralize PH levels and all impacted soil was excavated and profiled for appropriate disposal at an approved landfill. The remaining product in DOWX 40077 was vacuumed out; and afterwards, DOWX 40077 was cleaned and purged. An evacuation was initiated that impacted approximately 350 people for about 3 hours.

column168: During the rerailing and clearing process of intact NATX 250775 that derailed in an earlier BNSF train derailment on 9/19/06; a BNSF contractor’s side-boom struck the valve housing of this tank car, collapsing the housing cover onto the threaded liquid valve. The liquid valve that was attached atop a pipe extension on a four bolt pipe flange was forced downward by this impact and became cross-threaded on the pipe extension. NATX 250775, under pressure, released a small amount of product at the threaded valve-pipe connection. BNSF responders nearby, immediately depressurized NATX 250775 by opening the vapor valve; thereby ending further product release at the liquid valve connection. The product in NATX 250775 was transferred into tanker trucks and returned to the origin shipper’s facility to reprocess. Afterwards, NATX 250775 was cleaned and purged of all remaining product.

column168: During a BNSF routine inspection of hazardous material shipments in the railyard, BNSF 880162 was found to be dripping product from the bottom outlet cap (BOC). Detailed inspection by the BNSF inspector/hazardous material responder revealed that the top operated bottom outlet valve (TOBOV) operating rod was 1/2 turn open and the the BOC was approximately one turn loose. The TOBOV was closed and the BOC was tool tightened, ending further product drips. The drip impact was confined to a spot on one crosstie under the BOC. High density paper towels were used to wipe spillage from the tank car fittings and absorb spillage on the crosstie. Response was concluded by 1044 hrs. PDT, 9/23/06. BNSF 880162 was released to proceed to its destination afterwards.
column169: ENSURE SHIPPER'S PRE-TRIP INSPECTION PROCESS IS FULLY IMPLEMENTED AND VALIDATED AS IT RELATES TO THE TOTAL SECUREMENT AND MECHANICAL FITNESS OF ALL VALVES AND FITTINGS.

column168: A BNSF switchman reported UTLX 208119 in the railyard with a small fresh product stain on the side shell near the top fitting area. UTLX 208119 was carefully moved to an isolated track in the railyard to await further inspection. On 10/02/06, a BNSF hazardous material-environmental responder found the liquid valve partially open (1/4 turn) and the corresponding closure plug was less than tool tight. UTLX 208119 was depressurized and the product outage was checked and it appeared suitable. The liquid valve was closed and the closure plug tool tightened. All valves and fittings were secured by 1900 hrs. CDT, 10/02/06. All spillage evaporated.

column168: Airbags were recently delivered to American Honda Motor Co. (Torrance, CA) as priority mail, via the U.S. Postal Service.  The airbags were shipped to American Honda by State Farm Insurance Companies (Charlottesville, VA)in a card board box sealed with packaging tape.      It appears the box was originally used by American Honda to ship replacement airbags to a repair facility.  The box was a certified, one-time use box, appropriately sealed and labeled.  At some point, however, it appears the same box was shipped to State Farm, via Fed Ex (a partial Fed Ex sticker is visible on the box).  State Farm in turn, shipped the box with the airbags to American Honda.         Upon receipt of the box, American Honda discovered the airbags were not deployed, and were in fact improperly packed.  The exterior of the box did not contain any handling instructions, nor did it have the required explosives placard.  Once the contents were known, American Honda was concerned for the safety of its employees.  We were also concerned that the Postal Service employees and others who handled the box, had no knowledge of the hazardous nature of the contents.  Fortunately, the airbags did not deploy and there were no injuries or property damage.       Photographs of the box and contents are available for your review.  Please let us know if you would like copies.

According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While traveling on Highway 389 in Wagener, South Carolina, the Bridge Terminal Transport, Inc. vehicle was involved in a vehicle accident, which caused the truck to rollover.  Aiken County Sheriff's Department responded to assess the site.  Arch Wood Protection, the shipper, was contacted by the Aiken County Sheriff's Department to coordinate cleanup.  Hepaco, Inc. of Charlotte, North Carolina was dispatched to perform the cleanup.  Upon arrival on site, Hepaco, Inc. contained the free product, and inspected the freight.  Five (5) 55-gallon drums had released their contents, and the remaining drums had been dented and damaged, however, remained in tact.  Approximately 275 gallons of free product were released to the roadway, and within the roadside ditch along the Interstate.  Hepaco, Inc. performed the cleanup at the direction of Arch Wood Protection, which was overseen by the South Carolina Department of Transportation, and South Carolina DHEC.  Contaminated soil has been excavated, and site has been restored to preexisting condition.  Hepaco, Inc. coordinated disposal of all waste generated during the cleanup directly with Arch Wood Protection.  Soil was transported for disposal on 11/20/2006.  There were no injuries or exposures reported.    Please note, due to a contract directly through Arch Wood Protection and Hepaco, Inc., no information was released to the carrier prior to November 21, 2006.  Bridge Terminal Transport, Inc. is aware of the deadlines set forth by the USDOT pertaining to completion of a DOT 5800.1 Form.  However, could not submit report prior to confirmation of product loss and site cleanup.
column169: Since the release was accidental, and appears to be related to a vehicle accident, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.  Bridge Terminal Transport, Inc. will continue to reinforce safety guidelines and driver safety to all personnel.

column168: During a TAG (The Adherence Group) inspection, a carton of "Paint Related Materials, 3, UN1263, PGII FP 27C" was discovered in the shipment but was not documented.  The carton was marked and labeled properly and the ocean container had class 3 placards.  There was a delay in filing the report since the container had class 3 placards and there was an indication that hazardous cargo was present but the shipper seemingly failed to include the one carton.  The shipper was notified and provided a revised hazardous documentation that included the carton.
column169: There should be an audit step for shippers to confirm what is loaded in the container.  In many cases today, there are different people loading the container than those preparing the documentation.  Time need to be allocated to ensure that documentation on everything loaded is passed to the person preparing the documentation.  There should also be a requirement for the ocean carrier to receive the cargo 24 hours prior to lifting to the vessel.  Many undeclared shipments are discovered within 24 hours of cargo lifting to the vessel.  Many are discovered when the shipper notify the carrier of the need to provide updated documentation.

column62: Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage; Rollover Accident
column168: Flying J Transportation unit was heading on I-10 westbound and came upon a vehicle (SUV) sitting in both westbound lanes. Approximately two minutes prior, the SUV crashed into the guard rail causing catastrophic damage to the vehicle (dislodged the engine and transmission from vehicle). Due to the time of incident, the transportation unit did not see the SUV until it was too late to avoid the collision. The transportation unit impacted the SUV sending the transportation unit into the guard rail; it then traveled onto the concrete barrier of the overpass and across the westbound lanes of the Interstate. The unit then overturned and rested in the medium between the east and westbound lanes of Interstate I-10. Due to the impact and resulting collision with the guardrail and concrete barrier, the tanker and tank received impacts crushing the tank. Fuel leaked from the tank and the dome lids of the tanker unit. Impacted areas were the soil surfaces of the medium.  As of November 15, 2006, on site remediation efforts are continuing to remove contaminants from the medium area.
column169: The Arizona Highway Patrol Report Number 2006-049709 stated that due to the time, 0300 hours, and the darkness of the area, the driver would not have had the ability to see the SUV in a timeframe suitable to prevent the collision. The SUV was of dark color, had no running lights and received catastrophic damage, prior to the Flying J Transportation unit colliding with it. The transportation driver did all that was expected to maintain control of the vehicle.    Drivers will be refreshed to maintain visual contact with the road surface for potential signs of anomalies within their path.

column168: Part VI— Description of Events & Package Failure  A Taylor Oil Co., Inc. driver was making a turn through a jug handle with the green light. While crossing the lanes the light turned amber and a tractor trailer jumped the light and struck the tanker broadside in the rear tires, causing the tanker to roll one and a half times. During the rollover the probe holder in the manhole was knocked out opening a two-inch hole in the manhole cover. The compartment was full and the truck on its side caused the fuel to spill out of the opening. Due to the accident 911 was called and the Port Authority police, Elizabeth Fire, Union County Hazmat, NJ DEP, US Coast Guard, Port Authority Environmental and Staten Island towing were called to scene. These agencies initially boomed waterway around airport with hard boom. A wooden peg was placed in the two-inch opening to slow fuel down. Approximately twenty minutes into the incident, Taylor Oil Co. was called. Taylor Oil called HMHTTC Response and Bull Dog Towing as well as internal company Hazmat and managerial response. Taylor Oil Co engaged in a two week clean up with HMHTTC, DEP and Port Authority Environmental to totally mitigate the incident. The spill and leak could have been minimized if the public agencies would actually use the equipment they have rather than wait for private contractors to do the work.
column169: Part VII— Recommendations/Actions Taken to Prevent Recurrence  Specific to the accident site, the duration of the traffic light changing from amber to red needs to be longer. There are six lanes to travel across at the intersection. Overall ways to improve transportation would be to stop granting CDL licenses to individuals who cannot speak or read the English Language.

column168: Driver was headed to Baker City Oregon to deliver a partial load of Jet A to the local airport. While driving East bound on I-84 in the vicinity of the Dalles Oregon the driver suffered from an unknown medical condition that caused him to become unconscious while driving the vehicle. The vehicle slowed and traveled along the guardrail and when it came to a stop the shoulder gave away causing the truck to tumble down an embankment. The truck tank suffered a small puncture from the boulders that it came to rest upon. Reinhard Petroleum was immediately notified and in route to the scene within minutes. While in route Oregon Emergency hotline was contacted, the emergency hotline, and Environmental companies were dispatched to assist with the emergency response effort. Fire and aid arrived immediately to the scene prevent further spillage and medi-vac the driver to Portland for medical attention.   Approximately 801 gallons of jet fuel was released into the ground. No waterways were compromised by the release and environmental clean-up was successful.
column169: Unfortunately no recommendations can be made to prevent an accident of this nature. It is important to note that this driver possessed a spotless motor vehicle record, 30 years of experience, and was in complete compliance with all FMCSR rules and regulations. Medical events like this are impossible to predict and are a tragedy to all when they occur. However, we will always continue to train on emergency response, driving skills, and awareness.

column168: IN THE CARGO WAREHOUSE, DURING BREAKDOWN OF AN IMPORT SHIPMENT, ONE BOX OF HAZMAT WAS DAMAGED BY A FORKLIFT. ONE LITER OF CORROSIVE MATERIAL LEAKED ONTO OTHER BOXES.   THE LEAKING BOX AND THE OTHER WERE PLACED IN A RECOVERY DRUM. A HAZMAT CLEANUP COMPANY CLEANED OFF THE UNIT LOAD DEVICE AND REPACKEAGED THE OTHER CARGO. THE LEAKING PACKAGE WAS PLACED INTO A RECOVERY DRUM AND SENT TO THE CONSIGNEE WITH THEIR CONSENT.   THE EMERGENCY NUMBER ON THE HAZ MAT , SHIPPERS DECLARATION WAS NOT AN EMERGENCY NUMBER. IT TOOK SEVERAL HOURS TO CONTACT THE RIGHT INDIVIDUAL TO GET AN MSDS.   THE EMERGENCY NUMBER ON THE SHIPPER DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS IS "001-216-671-0050" WHICH IS ONLY A GENERAL NUMBER AND THE PERSON ANSWERING THE PHONE WAS NOT SURE WHO WOULD GIVE EMERGENCY INFO ON HAZMAT.LATER TOM BLOTCHER 216-701-4227 FAXED THE Dangerous goods Declaration. The local FAA was advised about the spill and the emergency number delay.
column169: we recommended to the consignee PPG/CLE that their sister company in China ( PPG/BEIJING) was the standard emergency response number that PPG uses ( I believe they said they use CHEM TREC) . column168: At approximately 0750 hours, 9-25-06, an M6 oxygen cylinder and valve assembly failed during the transfill operation at the Apria Healthcare Transfill Facility, 7910 Shaffer Parkway, Littleton, CO.    William Corrigan, Transfill Technician, had just entered the fill area to assist Howard (Burchard) with closing the valves on the M6 cylinders that had just completed the fill process. About half way through the first rack, as he was closing the valve on a cylinder, he stated that “it blew up”. The cylinder flew through the air and hit the fence, fell to the floor and started spinning around and then disappeared. (NOTE: The cylinder impacted the chain link fence separating the fill area from the walk way and warehouse about 15’ from the floor and was found to have come to rest in the cylinder prep area next to the fill area.) The valve was found to have separated from the cylinder and was still attached to the quick connect and pigtail.    Howard Burchard, Senior Transfill Technician, had just finished the filling process on 4 racks of M6 cylinders, most of which were new and being filled for the first time. As he started closing the valves Corrigan came into the fill area and started closing the valves on the racks on the other side of the line. Suddenly he heard an explosion, something hit the fence and then he observed a cylinder spinning and bouncing around on the floor, finally spinning out the opening in the fence into the cylinder prep area. At that time he ran to the control panel and started venting off the pressure in the lines. The end result was the loss of the 5.8 cubic foot of oxygen, compressed that was in the failed cylinder and the amount (unknown) of oxygen that was in the piping.    The damaged cylinder was quarantined. The rest of the cylinders that were part of the same shipment were blow down, removed from the racks and placed back in the box they had been received in and placed in quarantine.    There were no injuries or collateral damages as a result of this incident.
column169: The failed cylinder and valve were sent to the Pacific Metallurgical Company, 2828 South Robertson Boulevard, Los Angeles, CA 90034 for examination. The report of the finding by Shahram Sheybany, Ph.D. has been forwarded to Luxfer and to Wayne Chaney, U.S. DOT, PHMSA    The incident was reported to the manufacture, Luxfer, who has initiated an investigation of their processes in an attempt to identify the cause of the accident.
column172: Seamless cylinder made of definitely prescribed aluminum alloys

column168: Hazardous Material Incident Report         Date:                               9/07/2006    Location:                         Medley (CFS / WHS)    Transportation Phase:    Loading     Proper Shipping Name:  AMYL METHYL KETONE     UN Number:                    1110    Class:                              3    Packing Group:                III    Result of the Incident:      Spillage    Emergency Response:   In house Clean up    Damages:                        Under $500.00    Human Fatalities:             None    Evacuation:                      No         Description of Events & Packages Failure     While in process of loading a container a forklift blade punctured a metal drum right above the bottom rim perforating it and causing a two inches gash. The driver of the forklift noticed the damage right away and called for help, the drum was turned on it side  to avoid more spillage.  The length of the release was less than three minutes. Absorbent material was place on the spilled area and under the equipment. Drum was braced to a wooden pallet and the gash was covered with aluminum tape. After we made sure that there was no leak or odor coming from the damaged drum, the drum was isolated.  An environmentally response contractor will be notified Monday 9/11 to place damaged drum into an overpack.          Recommendations / Actions taken to prevent Recurrence:         The person driving the fork lift: Bill Reim, had attended the safety seminars and is hazmat certified, kindly recommend the type of action required.          Copies of the shipping documents ,3 pages including stuffing sheet / DGD  already faxed.         Prepared by Martin Morales 9/10/06

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: The box was found emitting a strong petroleum-based odor. Upon opening the box we found a used fuel filter, soaked with what we believe is gasoline. The FAA was notified, I spoke to SA Theresa Hailey. There were no markings, labeling, shipping papers, emergency response nor other indicators to lead us to believe the contents were regulated. The freight is being held pending an FAA inspection.

column42: PETROLEUM DISTILLATES, N.O.S. OR PETROLEUM PRODUCTS, N.O.S.
column168: PACKAGE WAS FOUND LEAKING. SPILLED MATERIAL WAS RECOVERED IN A SALVAGE DRUM. UPON FURTHER INSPECTION, THE PLASTIC CAP HAD BECOME UNATTACHED TO THE INNER CONTAINER. THE TAPE USED TO KEEP THE CAP ON WAS INEFFECTIVE. THE FAA WAS NOTIFIED, I SPOKE TO FAA HAZMAT REGION MANAGER GARY MOHR. THE FREIGHT WAS HELD PENDING AN FAA INSPECTION.

DRIVER KRUSIEC NOTICED A VENTING OF MATERIAL THROUGH A FOIL CAP AS HE WAS LOADING DRUM, SUPERVISORS MOVED DRUM INTO A TRAILER AND SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED TO EVALUATE THE PROBLEM. THE SHIPPER AUTHORIZED XML-CONWAY TO REMOVE THE FOIL SEAL, CHECK THE BUNG AND TIGHTEN IF POSSIBLE. THE BUNG WAS INDEED LOOSE AND MANAGER KITTELL TIGHTENED THE BUNG. AFTER TIGHTENING, THIS STILL FAILED TO SEAL THE CAP/BUNG. A SMALL VENT OR POSSIBLE CRACK ON THE NECK WAS PREVNTING THE BUNG FROM SEALING.

column168: UPON OPENING TRAILER, TRACE ODOR OF PAINT OR PAINT RELATED PRODUCT WAS DETECTED. TRAILER BILLS WERE REVIEWED TO DETERMINE TYPE OF H/M ON BOARD. INSPECTION OF FREIGHT SHOWED THAT SMALL AMOUNT OF CONTENT HAS LEAKED FROM SEVERAL DRUMS AND HAD DRIED ON TRAILER FLOOR. FREIGHT WAS WRAPPED IN SHIPPER ORIGINAL PLASTIC WRAP, AND APPEARED TO BE PROPERLY BRACED AND BLOCKED WITH PLYWOOD PROTECTION AND LOAD BARS AND LOADED INTO THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER. CLOSED INSPECTION FOUND THAT SEVERAL CANS LEAKED AT THE BOTTOM SEAMS AS A RESULT OF TOO MUCH PRODUCT STACKED ONTO THE PALLETS. LEAKS APPEARED TO HAVE STOPPED AS NO LIQUID COULD BE DETECTED UPON MOVING TWO OF THE FOUR PALLETS FOR INSPECTION PURPOSES. MATERIAL WAS LOADED BACK INTO SAME UNIT AND BLOCKED AND BRACED. REGION SAFETY MANAGER FRANK ANGLIN WAS CONTACTED AND REQUIRED NOTIFICATIONS SENT. CONSIGNEE WAS CONTACTED TO ADVISE CONDITION OF PRODUCT AND AGREED TO ACCEPT MATERIAL IN "AS IS" CONDITION. PRODUCT APPEARED TO BE SAFE TO ADVANCE TO THE CONSIGNEE AND WAS DELIVERED.

CSX Transportation, car inspector at Grand Rapids, MI Yard, 0702 hours, 09/07/2006 reported an odor and hissing from TILX 302228. Car had been pulled form the shipper’s facility the previous evening. CSX Transportation dispatched Young’s Environmental Cleanup, Inc., Flint, MI. Young’s Environmental Cleanup personnel advised at 0926 hour, 09/07/2006 that they noted a vapor leak at the “A” end liquid line valve. Leak was due to valve not being fully seated and its plug being less than tool tight. Young’s Environmental Cleanup personnel reseated the valve and leak stopped. They secured this fitting and the vapor line valve plug also was less than tool tight, but was not leaking. Shipper representative, Mike Sheaffer, on scene, advised CSX Transportation that he would conduct a safety review of this incident with his personnel that afternoon (09/07/2006). column42: AEROSOLS, FLAMMABLE, (EACH NOT EXCEEDING 1 L CAPACITY)
column168: This shipment was to be expedited in order to make service. When a FedEx Express employee opened the shipment first as a part of that process, along with various non-hazardous items (hard hats, camera, surveying equipment, 2 pair boots) it also contained one 184 gram aerosol container of insect repellent which said flammable on the aerosol. As the shipper had not offered the shipment with any DG markings, labels, nor with a shipper’s declaration it is believed to be undeclared dangerous goods. FAA agent Paul Klimas was notified. FedEx held the shipment pending FAA investigation.

column42: AEROSOLS, FLAMMABLE, (EACH NOT EXCEEDING 1 L CAPACITY)
column168: This package came apart. When an employee discovered it to retape the Dox, they observed the contents. It contained a 14 oz. degreaser which said flammable and toxic. As the shipper had not offered the package with any dangerous goods markings, labels, nor with a shipper’s declaration for dangerous goods, it is believed to be undeclared dangerous goods. FAA agent Janet McLaughlin was notified. Local Canadian FedEx Express Safety Specialist Guy Rouisse notified Transport Canada. The shipment was held pending their investigation.

column14: HWY 2NB, 5 MI W OF DUNNING, NE
column168: The client, Midwest Coastal Transport, contacted ERTS on 09/17/06 at 17:12 p.m. to report a tractor-trailer rollover on Hwy 2NB, MM245, Dunning, NE. The NE State Hwy Patrol was on scene and Accident Report #D06-5415-28297 had been assigned.  The accident involved a cargo loss of UN1805 and UN3265 hazardous materials. The accident impacted a 20 foot by 3 foot area of impervious asphalt roadway and an 80 foot by 10 foot area of soft, sandy shoulder. The majority of the impacted area was comprised of packaging debris from the cargo on this load. The liquid spills resulted from the impact of the 5 galLon containers that were ejected from the load out onto the pavement. The material was determined to have been released from the caps on top of the container. The spills themselves were restricted to several 1  foot square areas.    All the spill areas were neutralized with soda ash. The soft shoulder was hand excavated where warranted. All the contaminated soils and absorbent were drummed for disposal. One drum of waste was generated from the spill itself.     The remaining cargo was collected from the roadway. segregated. and staged for prcper disposal.

column168: Dennis Dement, Car Foreman, reported approximately two gallons of product released from the manway cover of Tankcar NATX 38274 located on Track 501, north of the Rip Track, in the Centennial Railyard in Fort Worth, TX. Mr. Dement advised there were no injures, exposures, evacuations, fires, or waterways affected. Michael Moore, Manager Chemical Transportation Safety, was notified and responded to the incident. Upon arrival and inspection of the car Mr. Moore advised that the two inch liquid valve was leaking due to being cracked open and the plug needed to be tightened. He closed the liquid valve and lightened the plug which stopped the release. Mr. Moore advised no further remediation was needed.

column168: At 1130hrs on 911-06, Frank Lerch, Manager Chemical Transportation Safety responded to a reported leaking tank located on the east end of RIP track 425, Beaumont Yard at Mile Post 280.03 of the Lafayette Subdivision in Beaumont, TX.     Upon identifying the car, Mgr. Lerch requested that RMCC make shipper notification via Chemtrec. While enroute, Mgr. Lerch was contacted by Chemtrec shipper representative Jim Dudzik, U.S. Operations Technical Services Representative and Chemtrec Dave Turner, Production Mgr.     On arrival, Mgr. Lerch noted the top and sides of the car slightly coated with product. Inspection of the frangible disk housing revealed the 165lb disk to be broken. Mgr. Lerch replaced the failed disk with a BSB 165lb disk which secured the car from further release. The coated areas of the car were then neutralized with a water-sodium bicarbonate solution.     No reported injuries, drains or waterways impacted. After securing, and neutralizing the car, it was released to continue onto destination.

Upon notification of the report of tank car GATX 3978 leaking from the top, UPRR Special Agent, Haz/Mat Toby Trevett responded to the Avondale, LA yard. After arrival on scene, Trevett observed wet areas on each side of the tank car, with no indication that product had reached the ground. Trevett also detected a strong odor of the product. Trevett dispatched technicians from response contractor, United States Environmental Services, Mr. Frank Piediscaizo and Mr. Herman Newell. United States Environmental Services personnel discovered that the manway gasket was broken leaving a gap of approximately two inches. The gasket was replaced and the tank car secured for transportation.   Trevett also related that an unknown switchman complained of nausea, however; he refused medical treatment.

column168: Ed Fedrick, Senior Special Agent, reported yard personnel observed a small leak from the bottom outlet valve on Tankcar TEIX 20013, at the Rip Track in the Hollywood Yard, Shreveport, LA. Mr. Fedrick stated an unknown quantity of product was released to the ground and he was en route to investigate. Michael Moore, Manager of Chemical Transportation Safety, was also notified. Fedrick, reported that absorbent material had been placed over the released product. Agent Fedrick attempted to secure the leak, but could not stop it due to heavy corrosion of the bolts that secure the valve to the tank car. A large bucket was placed underneath the leaking outlet valve. Agent Fedrick advised there were no waterways affected nor injuries reported. State regulatory agencies were notified. Mr. Moore contacted Roger Reynolds with Merichem Corp. about the problem and he advised that he would have Specialized Response Solutions responding to conduct transfer operations on 9/14.

column168: AT 0519 HRS ON 09/28/06, FRANK LERCH, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY WAS CONTACTED BY THE RMCC, AND ADVISED THAT BLOOMINGTON YARDMASTER HAD REPORTED CARMAN JOSE ELIZONDO JR. NOTED AN UNUSUAL ODOR IN THE SOUTH END OF THE YARD, AND WAS COMPLAINING OF BURNING EYES AND SCRATCHY THROAT. THE YARDMASTER IMMEDIATELY EVACUATED THE SOUTH END OF THE YARD, AND LOCAL EMERGENCY SERVICES WERE NOTIFIED. UPON BEING CONTACTED BY THE RMCC, MGR. LERCH RESPONDED TO THE AREA. WHILE ENROUTE, MGR. LERCH SPOKE TO TRACY FOX, VICTORIA FIRE DEPARTMENT BATTALION CHIEF. HE INDICATED PERSONNEL WERE GETTING READY TO ENTER THE YARD IN AN ATTEMPT TO IDENTIFY THE SOURCE OF THE ODOR. ON ARRIVAL AT APPROXIMATELY O81O HRS, MGR. LERCH MET WITH MR. ELIZONDO AT THE BLOOMINGTON YARD OFFICE. HE APPEARED TO BE IN GOOD CONDITION, BUT COMPLAINED OF BURNING EYES, SCRATCHY THROAT, AND REQUESTED TO BE TAKEN TO THE LOCAL HOSPITAL FOR A CHECK-UP. MGR. LERCH THEN SPOKE TO BATTALION CHIEF FOX, WHO REPORTED THE FOLLOWING. BOTH THE ELEMENTARY AND THE HIGH SCHOOL HAD VOLUNTARILY CLOSED SCHOOL DOORS. A TEACHER AND STUDENT AT THE HIGH SCHOOL HAD REPORTED AN ODOR, AND WERE ADVISED BY FIRE PERSONNEL TO SHELTER IN PLACE. COUNTY ROAD 661 LOCATED ON THE SOUTH SIDE OF THE YARD WAS CLOSED FROM THE INTERSECTION OF HWY 185 & COUNTY ROAD 616 FOR APPROXIMATELY 1 MILE EAST. FIRE PERSONNEL HAD CHECKED OUT THE HIGH SCHOOL, AND REPORTED NO ODORS IN THE AREA. A CHECK OF THE YARD WAS CONDUCTED BY FIRE PERSONNEL, WITH NO IDENTIFIABLE ODORS LOCATED. AFTER BEING BRIEFED, MGR. LERCH IN COMPANY WITH THE MANAGER OF TRAIN OPERATIONS, CHUCK HUFF, INSPECTED THE YARD. AT APPROXIMATELY O93O HRS TANK CAR CELX 23105, LOCATED IN SOUTH TRACK 20 WAS NOTED TO BE EMITTING AN UNUSUAL ODOR THAT WAS VENTING FROM THE A END PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE. AT APPROXIMATELY 1000 HRS, MGR. LERCH SPOKE TO DAVID YOUNG, UP ENVIRONMENTAL COUNSEL. HE ADVISED THAT PERSONNEL FROM THE CENTER OF TOXICOLOGY & ENVIRONMENTAL HEALTH WERE ENROUTE TO CONDUCT AIR MONITORING. UPON IDENTIFYING THE CAR, MGR. LERCH GAGGED THE PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE TO A MINIMUM, AND SCRUBBED THE REMAINING VAPOR THAT WAS VENTING WITH WATER. FIRE PERSONNEL WERE ADVISED THE RELEASE HAD BEEN CONTAINED, AND THE AREA COULD BE CLEARED, ROADS AND SCHOOLS OPENED. AT APPROXIMATELY 1O43HRS COMMAND WAS TERMINATED BY FIRE PERSONNEL, AND THE AREA WAS CLEARED TO RESUME NORMAL OPERATIONS. AT APPROXIMATELY 1O3OHRS MGR. LERCH SPOKE TO CELANESE SHIPPING LEADER IRA GORDON. HE WAS ADVISED OF THE RELEASE AND ACTIONS TAKEN. MR. GORDON STATED HE WOULD MAKE ARRANGEMENTS TO HAVE AN ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR ON SITE TO VACUUM THE REMAINING RESIDUE VAPOR OUT OF THE CAR SO THAT MR. LERCH COULD REPLACE THE O-RIN9S IN THE PRESSURE RELIEVE VALVE. ON ARRIVAL OF PERSONNEL FROM CTEH, AND ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR HMHTTC, ALL WERE GIVEN A JOB BRIEFING OF THE ACTIVITIES TO TAKE PLACE. THE RESIDUE VAPOR WAS REMOVED FROM TANK CAR CELX 23105. THE 0-RINGS WHERE THEN REPLACED IN THE PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE WHICH SECURED THE CAR

PAX BOARDED WITH OXYGEN AND ASSISTANT.  THEY HAD BEEN CLEARED FOR OTHER FLIGHTS BUT THEN WERE REROUTED TO JFK-RIC ON THE LEG I WAS TO WORK.  OUR FLIGHT WAS ABOUT AN HOUR LATE BEFORE BOARDING BEGAN WE SAT AT GATE AN EXTENDED PERIOD OF TIME.  DURING THAT TIME THE ELDERLY PAX CONSUMED HIS AVAILABLE OXYGEN.  THE FLIGHT WAS CANCELLED. ON 10/15/2006, WE RECEIVED THE MSDS STATING THAT THIS PRODUCT WAS REGULATED.THESE DID NOT LEAK, BUT WERE NOT DECLARED AS REGULATED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL. THIS SHIPMENT ARRIVED INTO WILMINGTON VIA FLIGHT #415, N752AX. THIS INCIDENT WAS REPORTED TO THE GREAT LAKES REGION FEDERAL AVIATION ADMINISTRATION ON 10/15/2006 ONCE WE RECEIVED MSDS FOR CONFIRMATION.     THIS SHIPMENT WAS NOT DECLARED AS A REGULATED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.     CLEAR OF SCENE: 0419.     THERE ARE PICTURES ON FILE IN THE HAZMAT OFFICE IN WILMINGTON, OHIO.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing; Valve Body
column168: Ron Alarid, Supervisor, reported Tankcar HOKX 112140 was releasing product from the top of the tankcar during switching operations on Track Seventy Six of the West Colton Railyard in Colton, CA. Necessary state notifications were completed. Duffy Exon, Manager of Environmental Field Operations, inspected car and determined that the source of the leak was an external reclosable pressure relieve device that had opened and did not reseat. Exon contacted the shipper and arrangements were made to have GATX inspect and repair car. Upon completion of repairs and cleanup, the car was released to destination.

column42: PAINT INCLUDING PAINT, LACQUER, ENAMEL, STAIN, SHELLAC SOLUTIONS, VARNISH, POLISH, LIQUID FILLER AND LIQUID LACQUER BASE
column168: Manager Cooper was contacted by Transloading Environmental, advising they had been contacted by APL to inspect a leaking container. Developed container APHU 601738 contained approximately 20 floor loaded pallets of 5 gallon pails of ‘distressed’ or ‘returned' various paint products. The 5 gallon pails were stacked and stretch wrapped to the pallets. All were distressed or leaking. Several cartons containing one gallon cans of various paint products were also distressed or leaking. All of the leaking pails and cans were placed into salvage drums for securement. Numerous pails were so severely stressed that they were no longer fit for further transportation. The stressed pails were also placed into salvage drums for securement. The residue paint was cleaned and the lading placed back into the original container for movement onto the consignee.
column169: ensure containers are in proper condition for shipment

column168: ON 9/17/2006, EQUIPMENT STOPPED FOR A LEVEL 2 INSPECTOR AT OR NEAR HOPE, AR.  THE TRAILER WAS SEALED BY THE SHIPPER.  ONCE THE INSPECTOR ENTERED THE TRAILER, HE DISCOVERED THAT ONE OF THE BOXES WAS TORN/PUNCTURED AND HAD SPILLED APPROXIMATELY ½ POUNDS OF MAGNESIUM DROSS, ONTO THE TRAILER FLOOR. HE ALSO NOTICED THAT THE CONTAINERS WERE NOT MARKED AS REQUIRED BY REGULATIONS.  THE AR INSPECTOR THEN SEALED THE TRAILER, AND PUT THE DRIVER ROY CHABOTTE, OUT OF SERVICE.
column169: WE HAVE TAKEN THE FOLLOWING STEPS TO AVOID THIS FROM HAPPENING AGAIN:    1. WE WILL NO LONGER MOVE HM UNTIL WE HAVE THE APPROPRIATE TRAINING (WHICH WE’VE STARTED).  2. ANY HM LOADS OFFERED TO US MUST FIRST BE CLEARED THROUGH SAFETY. THEY HAVE THE FINAL DECISION.  3. WE NO LONGER ACCEPT SEALED TRAILERS THE RISK IS TOO HIGH. DRIVERS/DISPATCH NOW INSTRUCTED TO INSPECT ALL LOADS.  4. WE ARE IMPLEMENTING A SECURITY PLAN FOR OUR FACILITY & PROPERTY.
